ce:section.ce:para:
The DPV method was employed to evaluate the linear range and sensitivity of the NCQDs/FeCoFe-PBA sensor under the optimized experimental conditions. The DPV curves of Ep for different concentrations at the NCQDs/FeCoFe-PBA sensor is shown in Fig. 8 (a)
                        . The calibration curve in Fig. 8 (b) shows that the NCQDs/FeCoFe-PBA sensor responds linearly to Ep in the range of 0.01–306.7 μM. Over this concentration range, the corresponding linear regression equation is: I = 0.038 CEp + 0.41, R2 = 0.999. The detection limit and sensitivity are estimated as 0.003 μM (S/N = 3) using 3Sd/S. In comparison to previously published Ep detection literature (Table 1
                        ) [60–66], the developed NCQDs/FeCoFe-PBA sensor throughout this work provides a lower detection limit and a broader detection range for Ep. Moreover, the Ep detection potential of the sensor prepared in this study is lower than that of most reported sensors. This excellent performance was mostly owing to the synergistic effect between NCQDs and FeCoFe-PBA: the introduction of NCQDs successfully solved the problem of easy agglomeration caused by the rapid crystallization rate during the preparation of the FeCoFe-PBA. Meanwhile, both NCQDs and FeCoFe-PBA exhibit superior electronic conductivity and excellent electrocatalytic activity, especially FeCoFe-PBA having a stable redox pair and good electrochemical reversibility, which is advantageous to the sensing ability of NCQDs/FeCoFe-PBA. Furthermore, NCQDs/FeCoFe-PBA exhibit a homogeneous and distinct core-shell structure, resulting in more active sites and electron transport channels. Because of the aforementioned advantages, NCQDs/FeCoFe-PBA exhibit great sensing performance for Ep while also providing fresh ideas and insights for the development of sensing materials.
